notes.text:
An update for libjpeg-turbo is now available for Red Hat Enterprise Linux 7.

Red Hat Product Security has rated this update as having a security impact of Moderate. A Common Vulnerability Scoring System (CVSS) base score, which gives a detailed severity rating, is available for each vulnerability from the CVE link(s) in the References section.
notes.title: Topic

notes.text:
The libjpeg-turbo packages contain a library of functions for manipulating JPEG images. They also contain simple client programs for accessing the libjpeg functions. These packages provide the same functionality and API as libjpeg but with better performance.

Security Fix(es):

* libjpeg: null pointer dereference in cjpeg (CVE-2016-3616)

* libjpeg-turbo: heap-based buffer over-read via crafted 8-bit BMP in get_8bit_row in rdbmp.c leads to denial of service (CVE-2018-14498)

* libjpeg-turbo: Divide By Zero in alloc_sarray function in jmemmgr.c (CVE-2018-11212)

* libjpeg: Segmentation fault in get_text_gray_row function in rdppm.c (CVE-2018-11213)

* libjpeg: Segmentation fault in get_text_rgb_row function in rdppm.c (CVE-2018-11214)

* libjpeg: "cjpeg" utility large loop because read_pixel in rdtarga.c mishandles EOF (CVE-2018-11813)

For more details about the security issue(s), including the impact, a CVSS score, acknowledgments, and other related information, refer to the CVE page(s) listed in the References section.

Additional Changes:

For detailed information on changes in this release, see the Red Hat Enterprise Linux 7.7 Release Notes linked from the References section.

notes.text: The cjpeg utility in libjpeg allows remote attackers to cause a denial of service (NULL pointer dereference and application crash) or execute arbitrary code via a crafted file.
notes.title: Vulnerability description

notes.text: libjpeg: null pointer dereference in cjpeg
notes.title: Vulnerability summary

notes.text: The CVSS score(s) listed for this vulnerability do not reflect the associated product's status, and are included for informational purposes to better understand the severity of this vulnerability.

notes.text: A divide by zero vulnerability has been discovered in libjpeg-turbo in alloc_sarray function of jmemmgr.c file. An attacker could use this vulnerability to cause a denial of service via a crafted file.
notes.title: Vulnerability description

notes.text: libjpeg-turbo: Divide By Zero in alloc_sarray function in jmemmgr.c
notes.title: Vulnerability summary

notes.text: The CVSS score(s) listed for this vulnerability do not reflect the associated product's status, and are included for informational purposes to better understand the severity of this vulnerability.

notes.text: An out-of-bound read vulnerability has been discovered in libjpeg-turbo when reading one row of pixels of a PGM file. An attacker could use this flaw to crash the application and cause a denial of service.
notes.title: Vulnerability description

notes.text: libjpeg: Segmentation fault in get_text_gray_row function in rdppm.c
notes.title: Vulnerability summary

notes.text: An out-of-bounds read vulnerability has been discovered in libjpeg-turbo when reading one row of pixels of a PPM file. An attacker could use this flaw to crash the application and cause a denial of service.

notes.text: libjpeg 9c has a large loop because read_pixel in rdtarga.c mishandles EOF.
notes.title: Vulnerability description

notes.text: libjpeg: "cjpeg" utility large loop because read_pixel in rdtarga.c mishandles EOF
notes.title: Vulnerability summary

notes.text: This issue affects the versions of libjpeg as shipped with Red Hat Enterprise Linux 4 and 5. This issue affects the versions of libjpeg-turbe as shipped with Red Hat Enterprise Linux 6 and 7. However, the problem is limited to the "cjpeg" utility and does not affect the library itself.

notes.text: get_8bit_row in rdbmp.c in libjpeg-turbo through 1.5.90 and MozJPEG through 3.3.1 allows attackers to cause a denial of service (heap-based buffer over-read and application crash) via a crafted 8-bit BMP in which one or more of the color indices is out of range for the number of palette entries.
